  How does the event loop work

   Node executes all code, registering any callbacks and when the whole
   script is executed it waits for an event: in other words some
   EventEmitter emits an event. When callback code is finished (shouldn't
   be blocking, but of course can register its own callbacks), next event
   in queue is processed or the code is waiting. If node doesn't have any
   callbacks registered, then it finishes.

EVENTS

   Analogy to DOM events: user clicks on a button (button is an
   EventEmmiter, click is the event). Many objects in Node emit events

   net.Server (EventEmitter) ---> request (event) fs.readStream
   (EventEmitter) ---> data (event)

  Custom Event Emitters

   var EventEmitter = require('events').EventEmitter; var logger = new
   EventEmitter(); logger.on('error', function(message){ console.log('ERR:
   '+message); }); logger.emit('error','Spilled Milk'); ---> ERR: Spilled
   Milk logger.emit('error','Eggs Cracked'); ---> ERR: Eggs Cracked When
   you write: http.createServer(function(request,response){}); you make a
   shortcut of: var server = http.createServer();
   server.on('request',function(request,response){});

Streams

   Streams can be readable,writable or both. In the request callback
   request is a readable stream and response is a writable one. Readable
   Stream is an EventEmitter that can emit data and end events. Let's
   print what we receive from the request: ```
   http.createServer(function(request,response){ response.writeHead(200);
   request.on('data',function(chunk){ console.log(chunk.toString()); });
request.on('end',function(){
    response.end();
});

   }).listen(8080); When you want to connect output of one stream to input
   of another you can use pipe:
   http.createServer(function(request,response){ response.writeHead(200);
   request.pipe(response); }).listen(8080); $ curl -d 'hello'
   http://localhost:8080 ---> hello ```

    Reading and writing a file

   ``` var fs = require('fs'); var file =
   fs.createReadStream('readme.md'); var newFile =
   fs.createWriteStream('readme_copy.md');

   file.pipe(newFile); ```

    Uploading a file

   var fs = require('fs'); var http = require('http');
   http.createServer(function(request,response){ var newFile =
   fs.createWriteStream("readme_copy"); request.pipe(newFile);
   request.on("end",function() { response.end("uploaded!"); });
   ).listen(8080); $ curl --upload-file readme.md http://localhost:8080 If
   used manually we would have to control the flow if, for example, the
   read stream is faster then write one. Pipes solve the problem.
   Otherwise you would have to write:
   readStream.on('data',function(chunk){ var buffer_good =
   writeStream(chunk); // return false if kernel buffer full if
   (!buffer_good) readStream.pause(); });
   writeStream.on('drain',function(){ readStream.resume(); });

    Show progress of upload

   ``` var fs = require('fs'); var http = require('http');

   http.createServer(function(request,response){ var newFile =
   fs.createWriteStream('readme_copy.md'); var fileBytes =
   request.headers['content-length']; var uploadBytes = 0;
request.pipe(newFile);

request.on('data',function(chunk){
    uploadedBytes += chunk.length;
    var progress =( uploadedBytes / fileBytes ) * 100;
    response.write("progress: "+ parseInt(progress, 10) + "%\n");
});

   }).listen(8080); ```

